## Error Handling

Silent failures are worse than visible ones. A blank screen that looks like "no data" when it is actually a network error misleads users and hides bugs.

### Never write an empty catch block

```ts
// wrong - hides the error completely
try {
  await doSomething()
} catch {}

// wrong - swallows error with no context
.catch(() => setIsLoading(false))

// correct - always log at minimum
try {
  await doSomething()
} catch (err) {
  console.error("[context] doSomething failed:", err)
}
```

Always include the caught error object in `console.error`. Use a `[ComponentName]` or `[hookName]` prefix so errors are easy to find in logs.

### Never silently reset state on failure

When a fetch fails, do not just clear the loading spinner. Show the user something went wrong.

```tsx
// wrong - failed fetch looks like "no data"
fetch("/api/lists")
  .then(r => r.json())
  .then(data => setLists(data))
  .catch(() => setIsLoading(false))

// correct - set an error state
fetch("/api/lists")
  .then(r => r.json())
  .then(data => setLists(data))
  .catch(err => {
    console.error("[ListsTab] fetch failed:", err)
    setError("Could not load lists")
    setIsLoading(false)
  })
```

Render the error state in the UI — a simple `<p className="text-destructive">...</p>` or a `<Callout variant="warning">` is sufficient.

### Route-level error boundaries

Every route segment that renders user-specific or async data must have an `error.tsx` alongside its `page.tsx`. This prevents a single segment's error from taking down the entire page.

```
app/
  products/
    error.tsx   ← required if page.tsx fetches data
    page.tsx
  profile/
    error.tsx
    page.tsx
```

Minimum `error.tsx`:

```tsx
"use client"

export default function Error({ error, reset }: { error: Error; reset: () => void }) {
  return (
    <div className="flex flex-col items-center gap-4 p-8">
      <p className="text-destructive">Something went wrong.</p>
      <button onClick={reset} className="text-sm underline">Try again</button>
    </div>
  )
}
```

### API routes

- Return correct HTTP status codes — never `200` with `{ error: "..." }` in the body.
- Use `NextResponse.json({ error: "..." }, { status: 400 })` for client errors and `{ status: 500 }` for server errors.

### Acceptable empty catches

The only case where an empty catch is acceptable is for **non-critical, non-observable browser APIs** (e.g. `sessionStorage.setItem`) where failure truly has no user impact. Even then, add a comment.

```ts
// acceptable - sessionStorage is best-effort, failure is invisible to user
try {
  sessionStorage.setItem("key", value)
} catch {
  // sessionStorage blocked (private browsing or storage quota)
}
```
